    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-10-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-10-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="303"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>303. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_BWH2" type="from">William H.
                        Brubeck</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d303fn0"
                        >Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> Library, National
                        Security Files, Countries Series, Somalia. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-10-11">October 11, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In view of his exchange with <persName corresp="#p_HSI1">Haile
                        Selassie</persName> on the subject of military assistance to Somalia the
                    President should know that: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Our Ambassador in Somalia has been unofficially informed that the
                            Somalis have accepted a Soviet offer of $30 million in military
                            assist-ance.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>As soon as this is made public we will announce promptly termination
                            of our own military aid program (no deliveries have yet been made).<note
                                n="1" xml:id="d303fn1">Telegram 221 to Mogadiscio, October 11,
                                instructed the Embassy to call on the President to express the deep
                                regrets and concern of the U.S. Government at the reported decision
                                of the Somali Council of Ministers to accept an offer of large-scale
                                Soviet military aid. (Department of State, Central Files, <gloss
                                    target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> 6 SOMALI)</note> The amount is
                            trivial (half a million dollars a year US, $5-6 million <pb facs="0509"
                                n="481" xml:id="pg_481"/> German and Italian annually which will
                            probably also end). This will make the Ethiopians happy.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>We will stay in Somalia with limited economic aid ($4 million a year)
                            and the Peace Corps.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Bill Brubeck</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d303fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
